avocado_tidy <- avocado %>%
  select(-Date, - region) %>%
  mutate(type = as.factor(type)) %>%
  rename(total_volume = 3, plu_4046 = 4, plu_4225 = 5, plu_4770 = 6)

First predictor

Now, our aim is to build a regression model for the avocado response variable in terms of the multiple potential predictors held in the data frame. Lets have a look at the associations of the predictors with prestige and with each other.

We wnt to build an explanatory model


avocado_tidy %>%
  ggpairs(aes(color = type, alpha = 0.5))

NA
NA

Now comes the manual model building part. Lets build seperate models and choose between them on the basis of r2

and diagnostics.

Lets start with average price

# build a model which tries to predict average price from plu4046

mod1a <- lm(formula = AveragePrice ~ total_volume, data = avocado_tidy)
mod1a

Call:
lm(formula = AveragePrice ~ total_volume, data = avocado_tidy)

Coefficients:
 (Intercept)  total_volume  
   1.425e+00    -2.247e-08

This equation tells us that the predicted averageprice will vary decrease by 0.00000002 for every one unit increase in totalvolume.

We can then use the summary function to provide more information:

summary(mod1a)

Call:
lm(formula = AveragePrice ~ total_volume, data = avocado_tidy)

Residuals:
     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
-0.98366 -0.29994 -0.03319  0.25498  1.82528 

Coefficients:
               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
(Intercept)   1.425e+00  3.012e-03  473.07   <2e-16 ***
total_volume -2.247e-08  8.470e-10  -26.54   <2e-16 ***
---
Signif. codes:  0 *** 0.001 ** 0.01 * 0.05 . 0.1   1

Residual standard error: 0.3951 on 18247 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.03715,   Adjusted R-squared:  0.0371 
F-statistic: 704.1 on 1 and 18247 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

So, what does this tell us?

It tells us that our r2 value is really low (0.037) and so we can explain on 3% of the variance.So thats not the most perfect prediction out there.


# set our plotting parameter limits (2x2 graph)
par(mfrow = c(2, 2)) 

# plot
plot(mod1a)

Our residuals vs fitted plot seems to capture the systematic variation well, and the normal Q-Q plot shows a little deviation from normality. Nothing too major here.
